<subSubSection id="1E4E412AA19E7DB1880ECB272CF835F8" type="description">
<paragraph id="DC0693B3E3931DA0B060B852F8EFFDF3" pageNumber="43">H. niger; alis hyalinis; abdomine clavato, basi ferrugineo.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FCABF50EA21DE576D489956995EB14FB" pageNumber="43">Male. Length 3 lines. Black: the antennae nearly as long as the thorax, the flagellum fulvous beneath; the face covered with a dense griseous pubescence; the mandibles rufo-piceous. Thorax thinly clothed with pale pubescence; the wings hyaline and iridescent, the nervures pale testaceous; the tibiae and tarsi pale rufo-testaceous, the latter palest. Abdomen clavate, shining and finely punctured; the first segment and the apical margin of the second, ferruginous; the second and following segments with fasciae of pale pubescence.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2446ABDB036DE43A3100652A84B9C363" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="C1FEEF3306A7E1DDF0CFFF354E76BC2E" pageNumber="43">Hab. Singapore.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B0E837DCC2B8C7CC997FF530621A9560" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="CDFFCFF4B967519ED4E24B967812CF2C" pageNumber="43">This conspicuous insect might be mistaken at first sight for a variety of &quot;H. ceratinus,&quot; but in that species the apical margin of the fifth segment of the abdomen, beneath, is straight, or very slightly emarginate at the sides; in the present species it is deeply emarginate its entire width.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
